```json
[
  {
    "file": "custom_components/lock_code_manager/text.py",
    "line": 27,
    "summary": "CREDENTIAL_TYPE_BY_CONF_KEY is a single-entry conf-key-to-CredentialType map hardcoded in the entity, separate from where conf keys and entity platforms are defined.",
    "failure_scenario": "When password (or any second credential type) lands, a contributor must remember this map exists in text.py, that the new entity's `key` must be added here, AND that async_set_value's `if self.key == CONF_PIN` branch (line ~157) must be extended. The mapping lives apart from both the CONF_* constants and the entity-construction list in add_standard_text_entities, so the three sites silently diverge: a new password entity renders with the default 0-9999 range (no bounds enforced) while the coordinator still gates it, producing a UI that accepts input the gate rejects with no compile-time link forcing the update."
  },
  {
    "file": "custom_components/lock_code_manager/text.py",
    "line": 120,
    "summary": "_bounds widens lo/hi to admit the current native_value to dodge HA's render-time validation, treating the stored value as potentially out-of-bounds.",
    "failure_scenario": "This is symptom-level: it silently makes the displayed min/max lie (a PIN of length 3 forces min<=3 even when every lock requires 4+) to avoid a ValueError at render. The deeper issue is that the system can hold a value violating current bounds (cleared-to-empty, or a PIN written before caps were known, or after a lock with a tighter range was added). If a future refactor removes this widening believing bounds are authoritative, every slot whose stored PIN predates the current capability set throws ValueError on state render and the entity goes unavailable. The real seam (the stored value is allowed to be out-of-range; only NEW input is gated) is encoded only as a comment, not in a type or method name, so it is easy to regress."
  },
  {
    "file": "custom_components/lock_code_manager/providers/_base.py",
    "line": 1161,
    "summary": "cached_capabilities (sync property) and _get_cached_capabilities (async populator) are two accessors over one _capabilities_cache field, with only the async one ever populating it.",
    "failure_scenario": "The sync property returns whatever the async path last wrote; it never triggers a probe. If the entity's _bounds runs before async_setup_internal's probe completes (or after a reload recreates the provider but before re-probe), cached_capabilities returns None and the control silently shows the default 0-9999 range with no constraint, while the coordinator gate -- which also reads cached_capabilities synchronously -- likewise skips the lock. A maintainer later adding lazy population to one accessor but not the other, or assuming the sync read self-populates, gets a cache that behaves differently depending on which door you enter, and the 'never performs I/O' invariant is enforced only by the docstring."
  },
  {
    "file": "custom_components/lock_code_manager/domain/slot_coordinator.py",
    "line": 241,
    "summary": "The validation gate iterates runtime_data.locks.values() (all locks) while the display-hint entity iterates self.locks (event-maintained bound subset) -- two independently-maintained lock sources for the same decision.",
    "failure_scenario": "Today these sets are identical (every lock applies to every slot, both seeded from runtime_data.locks.values()), so the split is invisible. But the entity's copy is mutated by _handle_add_locks/_handle_remove_lock event callbacks while the coordinator re-reads runtime_data live. If a per-slot lock subset is ever introduced, or an add/remove event is missed/reordered during a reload, the entity will advertise one range and the coordinator will gate against a different lock set -- the user sees a min/max the gate then contradicts (input accepted by the widget, rejected with a ServiceValidationError, or vice-versa). The boundary 'gate vs hint' is clean in intent but the two sides derive their lock list from different, separately-mutated sources, so correctness rests on those sources never drifting."
  },
  {
    "file": "custom_components/lock_code_manager/domain/slot_coordinator.py",
    "line": 261,
    "summary": "The coordinator gate builds a human-readable English violation string ('at least N characters', '{lo}-{hi} characters for {display_name}') inline, mixing message presentation into the domain validation layer.",
    "failure_scenario": "Length-range presentation now exists in two places with two formats: this prose in the coordinator and the numeric native_min/native_max hints in the entity. A future change to how ranges are described (localization, '4 to 8 digits' wording, exposing the offending lock list to the frontend) must be made in both, and the coordinator -- a domain object the credential-mgmt refactor wants kept HA-presentation-free -- carries user-facing copy that can't be reused or translated. The aggregate_length_bounds helper was deliberately built to keep UI defaults in the caller; this inline message-building reintroduces presentation into the domain layer it was separated from."
  },
  {
    "file": "custom_components/lock_code_manager/text.py",
    "line": 64,
    "summary": "_DEFAULT_MAX = 9999 is a magic fallback for 'no advertised limit' that doubles as the cap shown when capabilities are unknown, conflating 'unbounded' with a literal 4-digit ceiling.",
    "failure_scenario": "length_bounds already models true unboundedness as max=None, but the entity collapses None to 9999 because TextEntity.native_max must be an int. A lock advertising a 12-character credential (alphanumeric password type, once added) that hasn't been probed yet, or any credential whose real max exceeds 9999, is silently clamped to 4 digits in the UI -- and because the widening at line 122 only ever raises hi to admit the *current* value, a user typing a fresh longer-than-9999 value is blocked by the widget while the coordinator gate would have allowed it. The number encodes a PIN-era assumption (4 digits) into the shared fallback path that all future credential types inherit."
  }
]
```

Summary: PR 1279 wires credential length capabilities through a clean domain layer (`aggregate_length_bounds`, `length_bounds` with proper None-for-unbounded semantics), but several seams sit a level too shallow. The highest-altitude concerns are (1) the hardcoded single-entry conf-key map in text.py that splits the credential-type wiring across three uncoupled sites, (2) the value-widening hack that papers over storing out-of-bounds values rather than naming that as the contract, and (3) the gate-vs-hint split deriving its lock list from two independently-maintained sources. The `cached_capabilities`/`_get_cached_capabilities` pair and the 9999 magic fallback are lower-severity but encode PIN-era assumptions that the rest of the model was explicitly built to avoid.

